  "prompt": "Why I cannot use netsend commands?",
  "response": "The `net send` command was used in older versions of Windows, specifically Windows XP and earlier, to send messages to other users on a local network. However, there are several reasons why you might not be able to use `net send` commands:\n\n1. **Operating System Version**: Starting with Windows Vista and continuing through to Windows 10 and 11, the `net send` command has been removed. Instead, messaging functionality was replaced by the \"Windows Messenger Service,\" which has also been deprecated for security reasons.\n\n2. **Service Disabled**: In older systems where `net send` was available, the Messenger service had to be running. If this service is disabled, you would not be able to send messages.\n\n3. **Firewall Settings**: If the Windows firewall or any third-party firewall is enabled, it might block the port used by `net send` (UDP port 135). This could prevent message delivery.\n\n4. **Network Configuration**: If you're trying to send messages across different subnets or if there are network restrictions in place, the messages may not be able to traverse those boundaries.\n\n5. **Modern Alternatives**: As mentioned, modern Windows versions do not support `net send`. Instead, you should consider using newer alternatives for network messaging, such as PowerShell with `Send-MailMessage`, specialized messaging applications, or collaboration tools like Microsoft Teams or Slack.\n\nIf you need messaging capabilities on a current version of Windows, consider using those modern alternatives instead of trying to implement the deprecated `net send` command.",
